To create a Node.js REST API using the Express framework for managing a list of books, follow these steps:

1. Set up your project
First, create a new directory for your project and navigate to it in your terminal. Then, run the following commands to initialize your project and install the necessary dependencies:

```bash
npm init -y
npm install express body-parser
```

2. Create an `index.js` file
Create a new file named `index.js` in your project directory. This will be the main entry point for your application.

3. Set up your server
Open `index.js` and add the following code to set up your server:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');

const app = express();
app.use(bodyParser.json());

const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;

app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server is running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

4. Define your data model
For this example, we'll use an array to store our book data. In a real-world application, you would likely use a database instead. Add the following code to `index.js`:

```javascript
let books = [
  // Example book data
  {
    id: 1,
    title: 'The Catcher in the Rye',
    author: 'J.D. Salinger',
    publicationDate: '1951-07-16',
    isbn: '9780316769488'
  }
];
```

5. Implement CRUD operations
Now, let's implement the endpoints for creating, reading, updating, and deleting books. Add the following code to `index.js`:

```javascript
// Get all books
app.get('/books', (req, res) => {
  res.status(200).json(books);
});

// Get a book by ID
app.get('/books/:id', (req, res) => {
  const book = books.find(b => b.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
  if (!book) return res.status(404).send('The book with the given ID was not found.');
  res.status(200).json(book);
});

// Create a new book
app.post('/books', (req, res) => {
  const { title, author, publicationDate, isbn } = req.body;
  const id = books.length + 1;

  const newBook = {
    id,
    title,
    author,
    publicationDate,
    isbn
  };

  books.push(newBook);
  res.status(201).json(newBook);
});

// Update a book
app.put('/books/:id', (req, res) => {
  const book = books.find(b => b.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
  if (!book) return res.status(404).send('The book with the given ID was not found.');

  const { title, author, publicationDate, isbn } = req.body;

  book.title = title || book.title;
  book.author = author || book.author;
  book.publicationDate = publicationDate || book.publicationDate;
  book.isbn = isbn || book.isbn;

  res.status(200).json(book);
});

// Delete a book
app.delete('/books/:id', (req, res) => {
  const book = books.find(b => b.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
  if (!book) return res.status(404).send('The book with the given ID was not found.');

  books = books.filter(b => b.id !== parseInt(req.params.id));
  res.status(200).json(book);
});
```

6. Implement search functionality
Add the following code to `index.js` to allow users to search for books by title or author:

```javascript
// Search for books by title or author
app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const { title, author } = req.query;
  let results = books;

  if (title) {
    results = results.filter(book => book.title.toLowerCase().includes(title.toLowerCase()));
  }

  if (author) {
    results = results.filter(book => book.author.toLowerCase().includes(author.toLowerCase()));
  }

  res.status(200).json(results);
});
```

7. Test your API
Now you can test your API using a tool like [Postman](https://www.postman.com/) or by making requests from the command line using `curl`. Start your server with the following command:

```bash
node index.js
```

Then, make requests to your endpoints to create, read, update, and delete books, as well as search for books by title or author.

That's it! You've created a simple Node.js REST API using the Express framework that supports CRUD operations for managing a list of books.

